  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a psychological phenomenon where individuals from groups stereotyped as less capable in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics experience anxiety about confirming negative stereotypes about their group. For me, having grown up in Naples with a master’s degree but coming from parents who only had primary education, I’ve seen how societal expectations can shape a person’s confidence. When I was younger, I’d often hear comments like 'You’re not built for this,' which made me doubt myself even when I was good at math. This is why addressing stereotype threat is crucial—it’s not just about changing policies but about fostering a supportive environment where everyone feels they belong. In my time, I’ve seen how creative thinking and hands-on learning can counteract these fears. For example, my children, who are now in school, have been encouraged to explore science through baking and cooking experiments. This approach helps them see STEM as part of everyday life, not something intimidating. I believe the key is to make learning relevant and inclusive, so that students from all backgrounds feel capable and motivated. It’s not a one-size-fits-all solution, but by integrating creativity and practical applications, we can reduce the anxiety that comes from stereotypes. In the end, education should be a journey of discovery, not a test of what we’re told we’re not good at.",
